Formula:
text
ceil(log2(inputWidth))


───

Runnable — 4bit input
text
4bit requests = 0101

2bit irq =
PRIOENC(requests)

show(irq)

Output:
text
10

Because:
text
bit 2 = 1
bit 0 = 1

and bit 2 has higher priority.

───

Runnable — 8bit input
text
8bit requests = 00101010

3bit irq =
PRIOENC(requests)

show(irq)

Output:
text
101

Because:
text
bit 5 = 1
bit 3 = 1
bit 1 = 1

and bit 5 has highest priority.

───

Runnable — single active bit
text
8bit requests = 00010000

3bit irq =
PRIOENC(requests)

show(irq)

Output:
text
100

Because:
text
bit 4 = 1


───

Runnable — interrupt selection
text
8bit interrupts

interrupts.7 = timer
interrupts.6 = uart
interrupts.5 = keyboard
interrupts.4 = dma

3bit irq =
PRIOENC(interrupts)

If:
text
timer    = 0
uart     = 1
keyboard = 1
dma      = 0

Then:
text
interrupts = 01100000

Result:
text
irq = 110

Because UART (bit 6) has higher priority than keyboard (bit 5).

───

Runnable — CPU interrupt controller
text
8bit irqRequests

3bit irq =
PRIOENC(irqRequests)

1bit isTimer =
EQ(irq, 111)

1bit isUart =
EQ(irq, 110)

1bit isKeyboard =
EQ(irq, 101)


───

All-zero input
When no bits are active:
text
requests = 00000000

Result:
text
index = 000...

The exact value is implementation-defined and should not be relied upon.
Applications that must detect an active request should verify the input separately.
Example:
text
1bit hasRequest =
OR(requests)

3bit irq =
PRIOENC(requests)

Use:
text
hasRequest

to determine whether any bit was active.

